The data is based on questionnaries and school reports from two schools in Portugal. the data has been joined by common identifiers, and only students present in both data sets (both Portugese language and Mathematics) are kept. The students are of ages 15-22. The datasets describe the performance in Mathematics and in Portugese language. The data also provides information about alcohol usage among the students during weekends and weekdays. The data is wrangeled, so that alc_use shows an average between weekday and weekend alcohol consumtion. 1=very low consumation, and 5= very high consumation, and everything over 2 is seen as high alcohol consumation.

Relationship between alcohol consumption and age, sex, failures and grades (based on G3 -> final grade) I think that people under 18 has a lower alcohol consumption, since itsmore difficult for them to get the alcohol. Furthermore I think males drink more than females, since the peerpressure can be pretty tough in that age and males pressure each other more to party (based on own experiences). If a person has a high weekday alchol consumption, they are more likely to fail and have low grades.

exploring the predicting powers of my model

m <- glm(high_use ~ failures + age + sex + G3, data = alc1, family = "binomial")

the cross tabulation describes how many of the predications were right, and how many were wrong. In the top left corner are true negatives (predicted as not high alcohol consumers and ther werent), in the bottom right corner is true positives (predicted as trueand they were true), in the top right is false positives (predicted as true but were false) and in the bottom left is false negatives (predicted as false but were true). From the tabulation you can see that 98 predictions were false negatives, that is almost 26% of the people in the data. Only about 3% were predicted as false positives, which is not too bad. In general the predictions are not that good, which are seen from these numbers and from the training error seen below.

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# choose randomly 80% of the rows
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)

train <- boston_scaled[ind,]

# create test set 
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

#fitting the lda on the train set
lda.fit <- lda(formula = crime ~. , data = train)
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "purple", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col =classes, pch=classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 4)

The biplot of the standardized dataset is much clearer and easier to interpret than the biplot of the original dataset. Also, the results differ from each other as can be seen from the biplots. Now PC1 accounts for 53.6% and PC2for 16.2% of the variance. When we standardize a dataset, we scale it down, so that the values dont have as much variance between each other. This is useful in PCA, since it assumes that variables with large variances are more important than other, which can be misleading in the results. The variables also assume values that are easier to compare.This is the reason to why the results are different. The correlations havent, however, changed. the arros are seen more clearly in the standardized biplot, but the relations between them are the same. This happens because the standard deviation changes, which can be seen from the summaries of the original and then standardized datasets.

This week we are learning about longitudinal data. Longitudinal data is the name of data where multiple measurements is done at different times on the same subject. That way, we get multiple responses for each variable. The different measurements are intercorrelated,and the different variables measured can also be correlated to each oter. Hence,we can have two different types of dependecies in the data.

BPRS <- read.table("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/KimmoVehkalahti/MABS/master/Examples/data/BPRS.txt", sep  =" ", header = T)
RATS <- read.table("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/KimmoVehkalahti/MABS/master/Examples/data/rats.txt", header = TRUE, sep = '\t')

# Access the packages dplyr and tidyr
library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)

# Factor ID and Group
RATS$ID <- factor(RATS$ID)
RATS$Group <- factor(RATS$Group)

# Convert to long form and extract day numbers from WD
RATSL <- RATS %>% gather(key = WD, value = Weight, -ID, -Group) %>% mutate(Time = as.integer(substr(WD, 3,4))) 

# Factor treatment & subject
BPRS$treatment <- factor(BPRS$treatment)
BPRS$subject <- factor(BPRS$subject)

# Convert to long form
BPRSL <-  BPRS %>% gather(key = weeks, value = bprs, -treatment, -subject)

# Extract the week number
BPRSL <-  BPRSL %>% mutate(week = as.integer(substr(weeks,5,5)))

The first data used this week is the RATS data. It consists of observations of rats weights and weight-changes during a nine week period. The rats are separated into three different groups, and each group is put on different diets. In the second data, the BPRS, 40 males have been assigned to two different treatments. 18 symptoms, such as hostility, hallucinations, grandiosity and suspiciousness are being observed in the males weeklyfor 8 weeks. The observations are based on a brief psychiatric rating score (BPRS), which gives each symptom a score from 0 (not present) to seven (extremely severe). This scale helps to evaluate whether a patient suffers from schizofrenia or not.
